<subSubSection id="0F871F9533BD9481977DB2330232D27E" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="48A2BDA6AF3D4A5EEFEA7453E678E0FC" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6F6062B19F4F89E842846C79B05A4636" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="6C18981B16C13E03A426B0CD10544711" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Tradescantia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tradescantia decora" order="Commelinales" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="65F16DBDDB9A14D3D07BBD9F2340CC91" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Tradescantia decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to the central region of Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil; in the Atlantic Forest and Pampa domains (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="122F5A85EB89FED4F4023B6AB9A27E1F" captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Distribution of Tradescantia decora W. Bull. Yellow- Chaco and Pantanal; Olive-green- Pampa; Dark green- Atlantic Forest." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.104.28484.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/217956" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">19</figureCitation>
). It can be found growing as rupicolous, rarely as a terrestrial, in rocky walls.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="978E312A30671CF8469FF7D0DEFB096F" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="616ACFD0BF217C22C95B8832B80873CB" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CFA9CED8713BCE24861850015DB216FA" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">It was found in bloom and fruit in December and April.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9D80CB9048CE575C896B1A19DCA16393" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="4E6FD4C8B149FFAE1A9254D339C6E57A" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B79760F1FA908CDABF6BABFAAAE82DD4" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
The epithet &quot; 
<emphasis id="AEE53F5C6246FBBEFB17C0E2910417B0" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">decora</emphasis>
&quot; means decorated, ornamented, making reference to this species beautiful appearance, decorated by its lush foliage.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E5B7DD61F53947663600DC03DCB589E3" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="38F1C77611342E038671B6BEA6FBEDCE" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4CC1857F55C5AD1A20F6E73EF3031006" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="52E7AA3BC8D7E18F73C38C85CB1EFA04" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Tradescantia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tradescantia decora" order="Commelinales" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="1E6BD0E560A6FF98102B0B93BFD9051E" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Tradescantia decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from five collections restricted to the state of Rio Grande do Sul, one of them cultivated in Berlin and without precise locality. Furthermore, its EOO and AOO are considerably narrow (ca. 672.001 km2 and ca. 16.000 km2, respectively). According to 
<normalizedToken id="34A4F9B8AE1B7A74C84DFFF4EFD84C0E" originalValue="Bünecker">Buenecker</normalizedToken>
et al. (2017), this spe 
<pageBreakToken id="FF71A3EA747B2F89E489B61AEA735C58" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" start="start">cies</pageBreakToken>
is known to present small subpopulations, with its distribution range being extremely threatened by the construction of small hydroelectric powerplants in the next few years (
<bibRefCitation id="2E5ABB258F38E32A2576F7B0E94731A0" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5902/2358198014685" author="Marchiori, JNC" journalOrPublisher="Balduinia" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" pagination="1 - 16" refId="B27" refString="Marchiori, JNC, Canto-Dorow, TS, Büneker, HM, Essi, L, Breier, TB, Pontes, RC, 2014. Campos e florestas no curso medio do Rio Toropi, Rio Grande do Sul (Brasil): Retrato de um admiravel patrimonio ameacado. Balduinia 45: 1 - 16, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5902/2358198014685" title="Campos e florestas no curso medio do Rio Toropi, Rio Grande do Sul (Brasil): Retrato de um admiravel patrimonio ameacado." url="https://doi.org/10.5902/2358198014685" volume="45" year="2014">Marchiori et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
). This might cause most or all known subpopulations to become extinct in the near future, since this species grows in rock walls near water bodies. Thus, in accordance with the IUCN recommendations (
<bibRefCitation id="F27D0134397AA208FAC14BF2F3CB9A35" author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/" refId="B25" refString="IUCN, 2001. The IUCN red list of threatened species, version 2010.4. IUCN Red List Unit, Cambridge. http://www.iucnredlist.org/" title="The IUCN red list of threatened species, version 2010.4. IUCN Red List Unit, Cambridge." url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/" year="2001">IUCN 2001</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="6E428BF81C43ABBB2A5F10F4A831DCFF" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. decora" order="Liliales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="2820FBDD235D6D6EDAED0B67878D9F7A" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">T. decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be considered as Critically Endangered [CR, A2ac+B2ab(iii, iv, v)+D1+E].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8773F21DCA336A98E016A98C2E45839F" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="nomenclatural notes">
<paragraph id="36EEAB791DD72887F4AA8583C6AED6B5" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Nomenclatural notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EBE73860928981458B108AAE36A8CCDD" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
After analysing the original publication (
<bibRefCitation id="DC9C4626A8238FE9F67E9E9975BF2C0B" author="Bull, W" journalOrPublisher="2. Engelmann, Leipzig" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" refId="B6" refString="Bull, W, 1892. Tradescantia decora. A catalogue of new and beautiful plants and orchids 63: 3." title="Tradescantia decora. A catalogue of new and beautiful plants and orchids 63: 3." year="1892">Bull 1892</bibRefCitation>
), I have concluded that, like most species described in Seed and Nursery Catalogues, 
<taxonomicName id="8AFABC84006DAD4FD604617321E7BB9A" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. decora" order="Liliales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="A9E57AC2783BA7AAB65B4D02418F2329" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">T. decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was probably described based on living and cultivated material. Thus, no voucher was ever made for this name. Unfortunately, 
<bibRefCitation id="6D1B8366AC9E265E37B0FC4F9081DC29" author="Bull, W" journalOrPublisher="2. Engelmann, Leipzig" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" refId="B6" refString="Bull, W, 1892. Tradescantia decora. A catalogue of new and beautiful plants and orchids 63: 3." title="Tradescantia decora. A catalogue of new and beautiful plants and orchids 63: 3." year="1892">Bull (1892)</bibRefCitation>
does not present any kind of il 
<pageBreakToken id="781686A2AF9FC857D07B9F2A355C77C7" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" start="start">lustration</pageBreakToken>
that might be selected as the lectotype for his name. Thus, according to The Code (McNeill et al. 2012, Art. 9.7), I designate the specimen 
<emphasis id="47C17F41B08137ACF610E991831E2DC7" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Aona &amp; Machado 958</emphasis>
(UEC barcode UEC057324) as the neotype of 
<taxonomicName id="3F92D5F72D0F03FB0F841808F4F40A8B" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. decora" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="BF94C05417F1864135F7ED5DD82672C2" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
since it is in complete accordance with the protologue.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9A773A2AA3DEB6AC5F0966FED5CAC7C7" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="comments">
<paragraph id="3D0FA140248FDDEFEC4AA1F95C68DC52" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B030A535091F06C09C0C26870654F810" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
After analysing the protologue of 
<taxonomicName id="E9C7154E5FBA06A4D91CDBA5E58ADF1D" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. decora" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="E32070D60AFFD667AE92667AD01EE871" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="0C7864285CB6B3731F06778F2ECAED70" author="Bull, W" journalOrPublisher="2. Engelmann, Leipzig" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" refId="B6" refString="Bull, W, 1892. Tradescantia decora. A catalogue of new and beautiful plants and orchids 63: 3." title="Tradescantia decora. A catalogue of new and beautiful plants and orchids 63: 3." year="1892">Bull 1892</bibRefCitation>
), it became clear that that this name was conspecific to 
<taxonomicName id="9C3E63B316BBAC017E1C63CFB0E238DB" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. valida" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="valida">
<emphasis id="F9EBE8A2650EDD0D294D8827320A9BD0" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. valida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="65E5339DF4B38B2F0B5E5BE08918B615" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. multibracteata" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="multibracteata">
<emphasis id="45F45F6C12AC40DF9DBBBED0EBECB269" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. multibracteata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, due to its erect stems (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="83CF56990133C086AADB4F46C46D6BEA" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tradescantia decora W. Bull. A habit B detail of the leaf-sheath and the base of the blade, showing the long-setose hairs C detail of the base of the leaf blade, showing the long-setose hairs at the margin D details of a long-setose hair E main florescence composed of 4 - cincinni, showing the side view of a flower and its pistil longer than the stamens F detail of the stamen G flower at anthesis H flower at post-anthesis I sepal, showing the lack of a dorsal keel J flower at post-anthesis, with capsule beginning to develop K pistil L-M seeds: L dorsal view, showing the costate testa cleft towards the embryotega; ventral view showing the hilum longer than 1 / 2 the length of the seed. Line drawing by M. A. Rezende. The entire figure has been replaced, see the Erratum note." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.104.28484.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/217980" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">18A</figureCitation>
), spirally-alternate leaves (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CA5E19D58CD6D90B88255BD97B756717" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tradescantia decora W. Bull. A habit B detail of the leaf-sheath and the base of the blade, showing the long-setose hairs C detail of the base of the leaf blade, showing the long-setose hairs at the margin D details of a long-setose hair E main florescence composed of 4 - cincinni, showing the side view of a flower and its pistil longer than the stamens F detail of the stamen G flower at anthesis H flower at post-anthesis I sepal, showing the lack of a dorsal keel J flower at post-anthesis, with capsule beginning to develop K pistil L-M seeds: L dorsal view, showing the costate testa cleft towards the embryotega; ventral view showing the hilum longer than 1 / 2 the length of the seed. Line drawing by M. A. Rezende. The entire figure has been replaced, see the Erratum note." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.104.28484.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/217980" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">18A</figureCitation>
), linear lanceolate to lanceolate leaf-blades with truncate base (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1487DF70F81870C74B8ABCE008C2D935" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tradescantia decora W. Bull. A habit B detail of the leaf-sheath and the base of the blade, showing the long-setose hairs C detail of the base of the leaf blade, showing the long-setose hairs at the margin D details of a long-setose hair E main florescence composed of 4 - cincinni, showing the side view of a flower and its pistil longer than the stamens F detail of the stamen G flower at anthesis H flower at post-anthesis I sepal, showing the lack of a dorsal keel J flower at post-anthesis, with capsule beginning to develop K pistil L-M seeds: L dorsal view, showing the costate testa cleft towards the embryotega; ventral view showing the hilum longer than 1 / 2 the length of the seed. Line drawing by M. A. Rezende. The entire figure has been replaced, see the Erratum note." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.104.28484.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/217980" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">18A</figureCitation>
)) and, most importantly, all being restricted to the state of Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="49ED122D815D62CA32479656AB0FF041" captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Distribution of Tradescantia decora W. Bull. Yellow- Chaco and Pantanal; Olive-green- Pampa; Dark green- Atlantic Forest." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.104.28484.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/217956" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">19</figureCitation>
). Since 
<taxonomicName id="F584848C0CFBB7D1CCA06E1447F812B5" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. decora" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="B176670C608C0E3759C62B7A610B6DC2" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has priority over 
<taxonomicName id="A0270B0D7DD49E85626F8A22848E5432" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. valida" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="valida">
<emphasis id="A3245CE83E73D151478CC98C482506CF" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. valida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="937ED14420AA90858D3D66F1D4FA727D" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. multibracteata" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="multibracteata">
<emphasis id="92851BD535F32CADB58BC2BAC69E8150" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. multibracteata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it should be treated as the accepted name for this species. 
<taxonomicName id="CD98784ED6242A2A044BA9F8BBB75C6B" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Tradescantia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tradescantia decora" order="Commelinales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="2EE8705007EC7A032AB92F464E7FF9E7" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Tradescantia decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily differentiated from all remaining species of the 
<taxonomicName id="C6CC1BFA0E06025CDD04F36183D549EF" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. crassula" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="crassula">
<emphasis id="AE734DF39C92BA3A25FB3F63CE983B8A" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. crassula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group by the presence of supernumerary bracts, its spathaceous and unequal cincinni bracts, its main florescence being generally composed by 2-3(-5) cincinni (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6054FABCEDF23AC96178911C83222086" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tradescantia decora W. Bull. A habit B detail of the leaf-sheath and the base of the blade, showing the long-setose hairs C detail of the base of the leaf blade, showing the long-setose hairs at the margin D details of a long-setose hair E main florescence composed of 4 - cincinni, showing the side view of a flower and its pistil longer than the stamens F detail of the stamen G flower at anthesis H flower at post-anthesis I sepal, showing the lack of a dorsal keel J flower at post-anthesis, with capsule beginning to develop K pistil L-M seeds: L dorsal view, showing the costate testa cleft towards the embryotega; ventral view showing the hilum longer than 1 / 2 the length of the seed. Line drawing by M. A. Rezende. The entire figure has been replaced, see the Erratum note." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.104.28484.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/217980" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">18A, E</figureCitation>
) and sepals not keeled with caducous hairs at the apex (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5831DD5DBFF5E1342690472FC3DF8257" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tradescantia decora W. Bull. A habit B detail of the leaf-sheath and the base of the blade, showing the long-setose hairs C detail of the base of the leaf blade, showing the long-setose hairs at the margin D details of a long-setose hair E main florescence composed of 4 - cincinni, showing the side view of a flower and its pistil longer than the stamens F detail of the stamen G flower at anthesis H flower at post-anthesis I sepal, showing the lack of a dorsal keel J flower at post-anthesis, with capsule beginning to develop K pistil L-M seeds: L dorsal view, showing the costate testa cleft towards the embryotega; ventral view showing the hilum longer than 1 / 2 the length of the seed. Line drawing by M. A. Rezende. The entire figure has been replaced, see the Erratum note." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.104.28484.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/217980" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">18G, H, J</figureCitation>
). It is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="76D76CAF338B5823F6330038D396A48B" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. cerinthoides" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="cerinthoides">
<emphasis id="271F1165D90142CB1A83C7584A8234DC" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. cerinthoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to its sepals without dorsal keels (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="09113B5F008D0BD70C8B440DBA56573F" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tradescantia decora W. Bull. A habit B detail of the leaf-sheath and the base of the blade, showing the long-setose hairs C detail of the base of the leaf blade, showing the long-setose hairs at the margin D details of a long-setose hair E main florescence composed of 4 - cincinni, showing the side view of a flower and its pistil longer than the stamens F detail of the stamen G flower at anthesis H flower at post-anthesis I sepal, showing the lack of a dorsal keel J flower at post-anthesis, with capsule beginning to develop K pistil L-M seeds: L dorsal view, showing the costate testa cleft towards the embryotega; ventral view showing the hilum longer than 1 / 2 the length of the seed. Line drawing by M. A. Rezende. The entire figure has been replaced, see the Erratum note." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.104.28484.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/217980" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">18G, H, J</figureCitation>
). Nonetheless, they can be easily differentiated due to its generally linear elliptic to linear lanceolate to lanceolate leaf-blades (
<emphasis id="C37926A35304F082FC14CA08008AA568" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">vs.</emphasis>
elliptic to broadly elliptic or ovate to broadly ovate or obovate to broadly obovate, in 
<taxonomicName id="5938720E2B74E3A0A5E21359BF99E61F" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. cerinthoides" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="cerinthoides">
<emphasis id="091EF47AE64D04A934E5C550304E732F" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. cerinthoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), glabrous with margins setose at the base or until the middle (
<emphasis id="4D4AE509D7281DD6B541645E182790DB" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">vs.</emphasis>
pubescent on both sides or only abaxially, rarely glabrous on both sides and ciliate margins) and pedicels and sepals glabrous or only sparsely pubescent at apex with eglandular hairs (
<emphasis id="46B536A0B87E1EA700C74F8719B3EAE3" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">vs.</emphasis>
evenly densely velutine to hispid, sometimes with a mixture of glandular and eglandular hairs). 
<taxonomicName id="AEA3A2B77F704F04615169814A52FFF0" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Tradescantia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tradescantia decora" order="Commelinales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="D09E65AA3E44B703C4399A73C29DD146" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Tradescantia decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much more similar to 
<taxonomicName id="7EFC34AE5942B8A2AE6E49E90FAE0D57" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. crassula" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="crassula">
<emphasis id="04855806ED4B9D1B36A6350BDCE2781C" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. crassula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B5DA571E0B6DA7824E6A51349677FA73" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. seubertiana" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="seubertiana">
<emphasis id="C3365026832F3E8F3E6B5D7D56A586C4" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. seubertiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, due to their leaf-blades and sepal pubescence. These species can be easily differentiated by the pubescence of the margin of their leaf-sheaths (ciliate to shortly-setose in 
<taxonomicName id="CC4696F460CD6390E2CC25B1FFA7246E" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. crassula" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="crassula">
<emphasis id="D224999DF0A5CC2D18CC35D2284AAF40" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. crassula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; glabrous in 
<taxonomicName id="803B1BC76CADDCCB978172A1923219D9" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. seubertiana" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="seubertiana">
<emphasis id="E01FB17211E8ACD85D1532ABFD3FD19A" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. seubertiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and long-setose in 
<taxonomicName id="439750E78009645A4EEAD7E982678B70" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. decora" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="100B3FE785BBD55B406AA7A6391EB75B" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the pubescence of their sepals (long-setose along the keels in 
<taxonomicName id="0C14DB61E7D1FAA53EF0F6BA125021CD" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. crassula" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="crassula">
<emphasis id="C48BBF432D6C15462A9AD0C935CB1406" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. crassula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; glabrous in 
<taxonomicName id="04315D0DF427B2737F161B378B19B825" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. seubertiana" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="seubertiana">
<emphasis id="2CBA4F9DD5D7D8C91BF3D8EE3A9A4A92" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. seubertiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and glabrous or with few hairs at the apex in 
<taxonomicName id="9D2A8499C8A7A902078A03268F6D7C00" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. decora" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="11D837A68962DF8B640F5D2DAC7077E3" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by the shape of their floral buds (broadly ovoid 
<taxonomicName id="81E9EA8D75A51321A137419346DD71F7" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. crassula" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="crassula">
<emphasis id="65FE92700B09688529ACED41F6E34245" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. crassula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; ellipsoid in 
<taxonomicName id="EAF53B5DDA6EDF4846D9BF7FE23BDF68" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. seubertiana" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="seubertiana">
<emphasis id="13D0AA3DFA5652DE437808F9AE5FEDE8" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. seubertiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and ellipsoid in 
<taxonomicName id="D3692E6BD08E6CB9770CD988F9031937" family="Commelinaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. decora" order="Liliales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="8F2E80462068B3C4E1E91A9C6B483655" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">T. decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="8EE2CA19200FD78FF7609A923FBA3781" ID-Zenodo-Dep="1322245" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.104.28484.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/217980" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" start="Figure 18" startId="F18">
<paragraph id="A6E9018565F861458A09EE59DE176CEB" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="81FCD23286E5DEA13380C5FA3F12060E" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figure 18.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="1770687FF253F228E14E26AB9C825C5C" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Tradescantia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tradescantia decora" order="Commelinales" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decora">
<emphasis id="2DEE8FEF67D2C2165D0AE3D1EBAF6C74" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Tradescantia decora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
W.Bull. 
<emphasis id="3949400858C5A867B58684C6116B7CD9" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">A</emphasis>
habit 
<emphasis id="5E874C0FF362B2CACA672DC7279C711F" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">B</emphasis>
detail of the leaf-sheath and the base of the blade, showing the long-setose hairs 
<emphasis id="B29252F8CC6441DE0ADBCF9F7580CB8B" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">C</emphasis>
detail of the base of the leaf blade, showing the long-setose hairs at the margin 
<emphasis id="CC047EAD043C5C9DAA6523D9F48A80FA" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">D</emphasis>
details of a long-setose hair 
<emphasis id="F2BA3F0D18C55A2237C2B89A7EE2DB80" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">E</emphasis>
main florescence composed of 4-cincinni, showing the side view of a flower and its pistil longer than the stamens 
<emphasis id="4FF4DB2F8EAA0EF753102404AAF6A6F3" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">F</emphasis>
detail of the stamen 
<emphasis id="10157230F619FCD7958566C9A6381940" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">G</emphasis>
flower at anthesis 
<emphasis id="63F1278A56F208EB45C8B0865D4CE24D" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H</emphasis>
flower at post-anthesis 
<emphasis id="5BEBEE509710E5ED043FA3D6EA6CCC64" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">I</emphasis>
sepal, showing the lack of a dorsal keel 
<emphasis id="EB38C5C47B51F0C4F2E64B46F4C1BB53" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">J</emphasis>
flower at post-anthesis, with capsule beginning to develop 
<emphasis id="FE1941267A75B76EFC7D2B9965F3A5CC" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">K</emphasis>
pistil 
<emphasis id="71E6E3B2B70AC360C72042FE9D3559B5" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L-M</emphasis>
seeds: 
<emphasis id="EA29312A1BED89A68EA4502711837960" bold="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L</emphasis>
